==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*saltan'', from Indo-European ''*sal-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Saxon [[salt#Old Saxon|salt]] (Dutch [[zout]]), Old High German [[salz]] (German [[Salz]]), Old Norse [[salt#Old Norse|salt]] ''n'' [[saltr]] ''adj'' (Swedish [[salt#Swedish|salt]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌰𐌻𐍄]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[ἅλς]], Latin [[sal|sāl]] (French [[sel]]), Armenian [[աղ]], Old Church Slavonic [[соль]] (Polish [[sól]]), Latvian [[sals|sàls]], Old Irish [[salann]], Tocharian B ''salyiye''.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /sæalt/

===Noun===
'''sealt''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''sealt''')
# common [[salt]] (sodium chloride)

===Adjective===
# [[salt]], [[salty]], [[salted]]
#:''sealte flodas'': salt waters.

